# Coding Standards

Covers code-level decisions only. For folder structure and state patterns see `frontend-architecture.mdc`. For workflow and review gates see `workflow.mdc`.

**Rule precedence (full chain):** `story-driven-development.mdc` → `product-owner.mdc` → `mvp-guardrail.mdc` → `milestone-execution.mdc` → `workflow.mdc` → `coding-standards.mdc` (this file) → `frontend-architecture.mdc` → `testing.mdc`. When two rules conflict, the higher rule wins.

---

## TypeScript

### Annotate where the type is not obvious; infer where it is

```typescript
// ✅ Infer — self-evident
const count = 0;
const label = 'Active alerts';

// ✅ Annotate — not inferrable from the right-hand side
const severityOrder: Record<Severity, number> = { critical: 0, high: 1, medium: 2, low: 3 };

// ❌ Redundant noise
const count: number = 0;
```

### Always use `import type` for type-only imports

Vite runs with `isolatedModules: true`. Type-only imports that are not marked `import type` cause build failures.

```typescript
// ✅
import type { Alert, Severity } from '@/features/alerts/types';
import { useAlerts } from '@/features/alerts';

// ❌ Breaks isolatedModules builds
import { Alert, Severity } from '@/features/alerts/types';
```

### Prefer `undefined` over `null`

Use `null` only when an external API or DOM API returns it and you must match its shape. Internally, always use `undefined`. This prevents double-checks (`=== null || === undefined`) and aligns with how TypeScript optional properties work.

```typescript
// ✅
type AlertDetail = {
  resolvedAt?: string; // undefined when not resolved
};

// ❌ Internal use of null requires null-checks everywhere
type AlertDetail = {
  resolvedAt: string | null;
};
```

### Model state as discriminated unions, not boolean flags

Boolean flags produce illegal states. A component with `isLoading`, `isError`, `isEmpty`, and `isSuccess` has 16 theoretical combinations. A union makes illegal states unrepresentable.

```typescript
// ✅
type AlertsState =
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'error'; error: Error }
  | { status: 'success'; data: Alert[] };
```

### Exhaust every union — never let new variants fall through silently

Whenever you switch or if-chain over a discriminated union, add an `assertNever` call on the default branch. This turns a missing case into a compile-time error, not a silent runtime no-op.

```typescript
// src/lib/assertNever.ts
export function assertNever(value: never, message?: string): never {
  throw new Error(message ?? `Unhandled case: ${JSON.stringify(value)}`);
}

// ✅ Adding a new Severity variant causes a compile error here immediately
function getSeverityColor(severity: Severity): string {
  switch (severity) {
    case 'critical': return 'red';
    case 'high':     return 'orange';
    case 'medium':   return 'yellow';
    case 'low':      return 'blue';
    default:         return assertNever(severity);
  }
}
```

### Use branded types for entity IDs — provide a casting helper at the boundary

Plain `string` IDs are interchangeable by the compiler. Brand them and cast once at the API boundary with a helper, not with `as` scattered across the codebase.

```typescript
// src/types/brands.ts
type Brand<T, B> = T & { readonly __brand: B };

export type AlertId = Brand<string, 'AlertId'>;
export type OrgId   = Brand<string, 'OrgId'>;

// Cast once when data enters the system (API response, URL param)
export const toAlertId = (id: string): AlertId => id as AlertId;
export const toOrgId   = (id: string): OrgId   => id as OrgId;

// From here on, the types are enforced everywhere
function dismissAlert(alertId: AlertId): Promise<void> {}
```

### Use `satisfies` to validate a shape without widening its type

```typescript
// ✅ All four members required — TypeScript errors if one is missing
const severityConfig = {
  critical: { color: 'red',    label: 'Critical' },
  high:     { color: 'orange', label: 'High'     },
  medium:   { color: 'yellow', label: 'Medium'   },
  low:      { color: 'blue',   label: 'Low'      },
} satisfies Record<Severity, { color: string; label: string }>;

// severityConfig.critical.color is 'red', not string
```

### No `any`. No unsafe `as`. Use `unknown` and narrow.

`any` disables type checking downstream. Unsafe `as` (asserting a type that hasn't been proven) is `any` in disguise. Both are banned.

```typescript
// ✅ Safe narrowing
function parseApiError(error: unknown): string {
  if (error instanceof Error) return error.message;
  if (typeof error === 'string') return error;
  return 'An unexpected error occurred';
}

// ✅ The only acceptable use of `as`: narrowing after a runtime check
const input = document.getElementById('search');
if (!(input instanceof HTMLInputElement)) throw new Error('Expected input element');
const value = (input as HTMLInputElement).value; // compiler can't narrow this without the cast

// ❌
const value = (document.getElementById('search') as HTMLInputElement).value; // unguarded
function parseApiError(error: any): string { return error.message; }
```

