## Functions

### Single Responsibility: if "and" describes it, split it

```typescript
// ✅
function formatSeverityLabel(severity: Severity): string { ... }
function getSeverityColor(severity: Severity): string { ... }

// ❌
function getSeverityLabelAndColor(severity: Severity) { ... }
```

### Prefer `async/await` over `.then()` chains

Consistent. Easier to read, easier to debug, easier for AI agents to generate correct error handling.

```typescript
// ✅
async function loadAlerts(orgId: OrgId): Promise<Alert[]> {
  try {
    const response = await api.getAlerts(orgId);
    return response.data;
  } catch (error) {
    throw new AlertLoadError('Failed to load alerts', { cause: error });
  }
}

// ❌ Mixed styles within a file
api.getAlerts(orgId).then(r => r.data).catch(handleError);
```

### Early returns over nested conditions

```typescript
// ✅
function getAlertMessage(alert: Alert | undefined): string {
  if (!alert) return 'No alert selected';
  if (alert.status === 'resolved') return 'This alert has been resolved';
  return alert.message;
}
```

### One level of abstraction per function

A function that orchestrates calls should not also contain implementation details. Extract low-level logic into named helpers.

```typescript
// ❌ Mixes orchestration with implementation
async function processAlerts(orgId: OrgId) {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/orgs/${orgId}/alerts`);
  const json = await response.json();
  const alerts = json.data.filter((a: Alert) => a.status !== 'resolved');
  alerts.sort((a, b) => severityOrder[a.severity] - severityOrder[b.severity]);
  return alerts;
}

// ✅ Orchestrates named steps — each step can be tested and read independently
async function processAlerts(orgId: OrgId) {
  const raw = await fetchAlerts(orgId);
  const active = filterResolved(raw);
  return sortBySeverity(active);
}
```

