## Component Design

### Extend the underlying HTML element's props

Every component should accept and forward the props of its underlying element. This enables `className`, `data-testid`, ARIA overrides, and ref forwarding without adding explicit props.

```typescript
// ✅
type AlertCardProps = React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'article'> & {
  severity: Severity;
  title: string;
  issuedAt: string;
};

export function AlertCard({ severity, title, issuedAt, className, ...rest }: AlertCardProps) {
  return (
    <article className={cn('alert-card', className)} {...rest}>
      ...
    </article>
  );
}

// ❌ Closed — cannot add data-testid, className, or ARIA props without a PR
type AlertCardProps = {
  severity: Severity;
  title: string;
  issuedAt: string;
};
```

### Narrow the domain contract; open the HTML contract

Pass only domain data as named props. Let native attributes flow through the spread. Do not pass full domain objects when only 2–3 fields are needed.

```typescript
// ❌ Couples component to the entire Alert shape
type AlertCardProps = { alert: Alert };

// ✅
type AlertCardProps = React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'article'> & {
  severity: Severity;  // 3 domain props, not 1 fat object
  title: string;
  issuedAt: string;
};
```

### Composition over configuration

Use slot-style composition when a component needs to render variable content. Prefer this over adding props for every new variant. The signal is not prop count — it is whether the props still describe a single coherent concern.

```typescript
// ✅ Composition — caller controls layout
<Card>
  <Card.Header>Critical Alerts</Card.Header>
  <Card.Body><AlertList alerts={alerts} /></Card.Body>
</Card>

// ❌ New variant = new prop, indefinitely
<Card title="Critical Alerts" showBorder hasShadow isCompact footerAction={<Button />} />
```

### React 19: `ref` is a prop — do not use `forwardRef`

```typescript
// ✅
export function TextInput({ ref, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<'input'>) {
  return <input ref={ref} {...props} />;
}

// ❌ React 18 pattern — removed in React 19
export const TextInput = React.forwardRef<HTMLInputElement, Props>((props, ref) => ...);
```

### Derive, don't synchronize

Never copy props into state. Derive from props directly.

```typescript
// ✅
function AlertList({ alerts }: { alerts: Alert[] }) {
  const criticalAlerts = alerts.filter(a => a.severity === 'critical');
}

// ❌ Stale mirror of prop
function AlertList({ alerts }: { alerts: Alert[] }) {
  const [criticalAlerts, setCriticalAlerts] = useState(
    alerts.filter(a => a.severity === 'critical')
  );
}
```

### Always use stable, meaningful `key` props in lists

Never use array index as a key. Use the entity's stable ID.

```typescript
// ✅
alerts.map(alert => <AlertCard key={alert.id} ... />)

// ❌ Index-as-key breaks reconciliation when items are reordered or removed
alerts.map((alert, i) => <AlertCard key={i} ... />)
```

