## Hooks

### One hook, one concern

A hook that fetches data AND manages local UI state is two hooks. The line: if the hook's return value would make sense as a named type, it is probably one concern. If the return value is an unrelated mixture, split it.

```typescript
// ✅ One concern each — useAlerts always takes a branded OrgId parameter
const { data, isPending, isError } = useAlerts(orgId);     // data fetching
const { isOpen, open, close } = useDisclosure();            // UI state

// ❌ One hook doing both — untestable in isolation
const { data, isPending, isOpen, open, close } = useAlertsWithPanel(orgId);
```

### Use `useEffect` only for external synchronization

`useEffect` syncs React state with something outside React: a timer, a WebSocket, a DOM API, a third-party library. It is not for computing derived values or responding to user events.

```typescript
// ✅ External sync — DOM title must stay in sync with data
useEffect(() => {
  document.title = `${criticalCount} critical alerts`;
}, [criticalCount]);

// ❌ Derived state — compute directly
const [criticalCount, setCriticalCount] = useState(0);
useEffect(() => {
  setCriticalCount(alerts.filter(a => a.severity === 'critical').length);
}, [alerts]);
```

### `useMemo` and `useCallback`: distinguish calculation cost from referential stability

There are two separate reasons to memoize. Apply the right test for each.

| Reason | When to use | Test |
|---|---|---|
| **Expensive calculation** | Only after profiling shows a real cost | Does this run in >1ms? Measure first. |
| **Referential stability** | When the value is a `useEffect` dependency or a prop to a memoized child | Would removing this cause an infinite loop or redundant re-render? |

```typescript
// ✅ Referential stability — must be stable or useEffect runs on every render
const queryParams = useMemo(() => ({ orgId, status: 'active' }), [orgId]);
useEffect(() => { fetchAlerts(queryParams); }, [queryParams]);

// ✅ Callback stability — passed to a memoized child
const handleDismiss = useCallback((id: AlertId) => dismiss(id), [dismiss]);

// ❌ Memoizing a trivial calculation — overhead exceeds any benefit
const label = useMemo(() => severity.toUpperCase(), [severity]);
```

### Type event handlers explicitly

Never use `any` on event parameters. Use React's built-in event types.

```typescript
// ✅
function handleChange(event: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) {
  setValue(event.target.value);
}

function handleSubmit(event: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) {
  event.preventDefault();
  submitForm();
}

// ❌
function handleChange(e: any) { setValue(e.target.value); }
```

