## Accessibility

### Semantic HTML is the baseline — ARIA augments, it does not replace

Every interactive element must be a native interactive element. If you use `<div>` or `<span>` with an `onClick`, you own focus management, keyboard handling, and role announcement.

```typescript
// ✅
<button onClick={handleDismiss}>Dismiss</button>

// ❌ You now must add tabIndex, onKeyDown, role, and aria-label manually
<div onClick={handleDismiss}>Dismiss</div>
```

### Required on every interactive component

```typescript
// Icon-only buttons: visible label via aria-label
<button aria-label="Dismiss alert: Exposed API key">
  <XIcon aria-hidden="true" />
</button>

// Form inputs: always associated with a label
<label htmlFor="severity-filter">Filter by severity</label>
<select id="severity-filter" value={severity} onChange={handleChange} />

// Loading state: use visually-hidden text in a live region, not an empty string
// An empty live region on some screen readers announces "blank" — use a hidden span
<span role="status" aria-live="polite" className="sr-only">
  {isPending ? 'Loading alerts, please wait.' : 'Alerts loaded.'}
</span>
```

### Color is an enhancement, never the only signal

Every severity level must carry a text label, an icon, or a pattern — not only a color. Users with color blindness must be able to distinguish `critical` from `low`.

